solutions.content:
Let's understand the problem and solve it step by step:

```
Given an array of integers arr, you are initially positioned at the first index of the array.

In one step you can jump from index i to index:

i + 1 where: i + 1 < arr.length.
i - 1 where: i - 1 >= 0.
j where: arr[i] == arr[j] and i != j.
Return the minimum number of steps to reach the last index of the array.
```

So from an index you can go to index + 1, index -1, and to the index where the arr[index] is same.
Consider each index as a node and take this as finding the shortest distance between source and destination !! 
![image](https://assets.leetcode.com/users/images/40109ce8-2918-4ccf-a018-3f5d5b9a01f4_1651818625.0956626.jpeg)

Now lets understand the code step by step !!

 **Step 1 :**   Take a map and map the values to the indices its present in the given array
 **Step 2 :**  Take a visited array and init the 0th index as True and now init a queue ( BFS BABY !! ) 
 and then push the 0th index, cause its the source
 **Step 3 :**  Usual BFS !! take the front element, pop it and check if its equal to destination index, if yes, return steps
 **Step 4 :**  Now take a vector and use the & because, you dont want to create copies and run out of memory and then push the index + 1 and index -1 into it
 **Step 5 :**  Now we have a vector of indices where that current index can jump to, and now check if the index is in bounds, and check if its visited or not !! and if every condtion satisfies, mark that index as visited and push it into the queue
 **Step 6 :**  ***THE MOST IMP STEP !!*** - You must remove the mapped indices to the curr node as keeping them will give you TLE, imagine a case where every value is 100, 100, 100, . i+1, i-1....it'lll loop forever !! 
 **Step 7:** As usual, increment the steps by 1


```
    int minJumps(vector<int>& arr){
        //step 1;
        int n = arr.size();
        unordered_map<int, vector<int>> indicesOfValue;
        for (int i = 0; i < n; i++){
            indicesOfValue[arr[i]].push_back(i);
        }
        //step 2;
        vector<bool> visited(n);
        visited[0] = true;
        queue<int> q;
        q.push(0);
        int step = 0;
        //step 3
        while (!q.empty()) {
            for (int size = q.size(); size > 0; --size) {
                int i = q.front();
                q.pop();
                if (i == n - 1){ // Reached to last index
                    return step;
                }
                // step 4;
                vector<int>& next = indicesOfValue[arr[i]];
                next.push_back(i - 1);
                next.push_back(i + 1);
                // step 5
                for (int j : next) {
                    if (j >= 0 && j < n && !visited[j]) {
                        visited[j] = true;
                        q.push(j);
                    }
                }
                // step 6
                indicesOfValue[arr[i]].clear(); // avoid later lookup indicesOfValue arr[i]
            }
            // step 7
            step++;
        }
        return 0;
    }
```

