solutions.content:
As most people have already pointed out, this problem can be reduced to a basic shortest path problem, where edges have uniform weight of 1. This means we can use a BFS to get the answer quite easily. There are a few things to realize here though.
1. The indices of the argument array can be thought of as the vertices in a graph.
2. You use the "rules" of the game to determine the structure of the graph, as in, how the vertices are connected.
3. If there are multiple values in the argument array in a row which are the same (i.e. if arr was {1, 2, 2, 2, 2, 7}), you technically only need to consider the end-points of this sub-array. That is, you could treat the array as if it was {1, 2, 2, 7} and end up with the same result. Doing this will increase the efficiency of the algorithm in some cases and one of these cases was specifically tested for (final test case).
```java
public class Solution {
    public int MinJumps(int[] arr) {
        if (arr.Length == 1) return 0;        

        // Basic shortest path setup:
        int[] d = new int[arr.Length];                                      // Tracks # of jumps from index 0
        Dictionary<int, List<int>> vd = new Dictionary<int, List<int>>();   // Maps values to indices
        bool[] seen = new bool[arr.Length];                                 // Tracks which indices have been seen
        Queue<int> q = new Queue<int>();                                    // BFS queue

        // Initializing "vd"
        for (int i = 0; i < arr.Length; i++) {
            if (!vd.ContainsKey(arr[i])) vd[arr[i]] = new List<int>() { i };
            else {
                vd[arr[i]].Add(i);
                // If there are multiple values that are equal in a row, we only want the endpoints for extra efficiency.
                // This is needed to pass the final test case.
                while (i < arr.Length - 1 && arr[i] == arr[i + 1]) i++;
                if (vd[arr[i]][vd[arr[i]].Count - 1] != i) vd[arr[i]].Add(i);
            }
        }

        // Setting known values
        d[0] = 0;               // # of jumps to index 0 from index 0 is obviously 0
        seen[0] = true;         // We've seen index 0
        q.Enqueue(0);           // Queue index 0

        while (q.Count > 0) {
            int u = q.Dequeue();                                // Dequeue (standard BFS)
            foreach (int v in Adj(arr, u, vd))                  // Iterate over "adjacent vertices" (indices we can jump to)
                if (!seen[v]) {                                 // We only need to consider "unseen" vertices
                    seen[v] = true;                             // Mark "vertex" (index) as seen
                    d[v] = 1 + d[u];                            // Record # of jumps from "source vertex" (index 0)
                    if (v == arr.Length - 1) return d[v];       // As soon as we reach the last index, we are done.
                    q.Enqueue(v);                               // Queue up the unseen adjacent "vertex" (standard BFS)
                }
        }
        return -1;      // Shouldn't ever return this, since there is always a "path" from index 0 to the last index.
    }

    // Returns a list of "adjacent" vertices, using the rules of the game.
    public static List<int> Adj(int[] arr, int i, Dictionary<int, List<int>> valueDict) {
        List<int> res = new List<int>();
        if (i > 0)res.Add(i - 1);                   // If i > 0, we can jump to the previous index
        if (i < arr.Length - 1)res.Add(i + 1);      // If i < arr.Length, we can jump to the next index

        // We can also jump to any index where the values are equal.
        valueDict[arr[i]].ForEach(index => { if (index != i) res.Add(index); });
        return res;
    }
}
```

