solutions.content:
This problem is oddly a hard, but all it takes it is just to recognise we have a graph to navigate from a starting point (the first element of `arr`) to an ending one (the last node of `arr`), following rules; and usually when we need to compute how many steps it takes to come out of a graph, a BFS approach is a solid one!

To do so, we will first rule an edge case that would make any further effort pointless (when the array has `1` or `2` elements, the result is trivially the `arr.size() - 1`, no way to do less steps than that) and then declare a few support variables:
* `res` will store the current number of "steps" we have made so far (ie: how many BFS outer loop iterations we have ground to this point);
* `len` will store the length of the the original input;
* `qLen` will store the length of our `q`, initially set to `1`, since we will always have a sole starting point;
* `curr`, `prev` and `nxt` will be used in our inner BFS loop to keep track of what node we are currently processing and its neighbours;
* `target` stores our final destination, initialised with the value of the last element of `arr`;
* `connected` is an array showing us how similarly valued nodes are linked, forming the backbone of our graph traversal logic later;
* `unexplored` will keep track of the nodes we must still visit;
* `mustContinue` is a microoptimisation to let us know when we are in the last or penultimate cycle of our BFS search, initially set to `true`;
* `q` is the queue that will store the current and next level of our traversal, as in most standard BFS approaches - initially set to contain only the first node (our starting point).

We will then initialise all the values in `unexplored` to be `true` and populate `connected` so that each value of `arr` (key) will tell use what nodes share it and are thus linked (value).

Okay, time for the main course, our BFS loops!

We  will have a main loop that will as long as we have a reason to go on (ie: `mustContinue != false`) and in it we will:
* run our level traversal, valid as long as `qLen-- != 0`, that is to say it will run `qLen` times and:
	* extract the current front of `q` and assign its value to `curr`;
	* pop that element out of the queue;
	* check if we reached our target, in which case we can just stop here and `return` `res`;
	* check if we will reach it on the next run (ie: `arr[curr] == target`, meaning we are on a cell that can teleport us to destination), in which case we do not quit immediately (we might have in the queue some node which is ALREADY the destination, so one less step!), but flag this situation turning `mustContinue` to `false`;
	* in case `mustContinue` is still `true`, we will then:
		* flag the current node as explored;
		* check the previous node `prev = curr - 1`, assuming it was not explored already or out of bonds, adding it to the queue;
		* check the next node `nxt = curr - 1`, assuming it was not explored already or out of bonds, adding it to the queue;
		* check all the connected nodes (if any) adding them to the queue (we know they were all not explored yet, since once you explore one of the connected ones, you get them all) and then removing that subnetwork from `connected`, in order to avoid parsing it again;
* prepare for the next iteration, increasing `res` by `1` and updating `qLen` with its new value.

Finally, if we reached the end of the loop, we can just `return` `res` :)

The code:

```cpp
class Solution {
public:
    int minJumps(vector<int>& arr) {
        // edge cases
        if (arr.size() < 3) return arr.size() - 1;
        // support variables
        int res = 0, len = arr.size(), qLen = 1, curr, prev, nxt, target = arr.back();
        unordered_map<int, vector<int>> connected;
        bool unexplored[len], mustContinue = true;
        queue<int> q{{0}};
        // preparing unexplored and connected
        fill(unexplored, unexplored + len--, true);
        for (int i = 0; i <= len; i++) connected[arr[i]].push_back(i);
		// BFS time!
        while (mustContinue) {
			// level traversal
            while (qLen--) {
                // extracting the current front from the q and checking if we arrived
                curr = q.front();
                q.pop();
                if (curr == len) return res;
                // checking if we will go there in the next step
                if (arr[curr] == target) mustContinue = false;
                // the rest of the logic matters only if we know we have to proceed
                if (mustContinue) {
                    // marking curr as unexplored
                    unexplored[curr] = false;
                    // checking before curr
                    prev = curr - 1;
                    if (prev >= 0 && unexplored[prev]) q.push(prev);
                    // checking after curr
                    nxt = curr + 1;
                    if (nxt <= len && unexplored[nxt]) q.push(nxt);
                    // checking the connected ones if any and clearing that subnetwork
                    for (int conn: connected[arr[curr]]) q.push(conn);
                    connected[arr[curr]].clear();
                }
            }
            // preparing for the next loop
            res++;
            qLen = q.size();
        }
        return res;
    }
};
```
Can we do better?

Well, yes, burning a bit more memory for the `explored` boolean maps, so that we have now `2` of them (and `2` queues, but that would actually use less memory overall) to run the same logic, but as a double ended BFS.

This alternative is much faster on average and the extra memory consumption is overall moderate:

```cpp
class Solution {
public:
    int minJumps(vector<int>& arr) {
        // edge cases
        if (arr.size() < 3) return arr.size() - 1;
        // support variables
        int res = -1, len = arr.size(), qLen = 1, curr, prev, nxt, target = arr.back();
        unordered_map<int, vector<int>> connected;
        bool *currExplored = new bool[len], *nextExplored = new bool[len];
        queue<int> currQ{{0}}, nextQ{{len - 1}};
        // preparing unexplored and connected
        fill(currExplored + 1, currExplored + len, false);
        fill(nextExplored, nextExplored + --len, false);
        currExplored[0] = true;
        nextExplored[len] = true;
        for (int i = 0; i <= len; i++) connected[arr[i]].push_back(i);
		// BFS time!
        while (qLen) {
			// level traversal
            while (qLen--) {
                // extracting the current front from the q and checking if we arrived
                curr = currQ.front();
                currQ.pop();
                if (nextExplored[curr]) return res;
                // marking curr as unexplored
                currExplored[curr] = true;
                // checking before curr
                prev = curr - 1;
                if (prev >= 0 && !currExplored[prev]) currQ.push(prev);
                // checking after curr
                nxt = curr + 1;
                if (nxt <= len && !currExplored[nxt]) currQ.push(nxt);
                // checking the connected ones if any and clearing that subnetwork
                for (int conn: connected[arr[curr]]) currQ.push(conn);
                connected[arr[curr]].clear();
			}
			// preparing for the next loop
			res++;
			qLen = nextQ.size();
			swap(currQ, nextQ);
            swap(currExplored, nextExplored);
			// swap(currExplored, nextExplored);
        }
        return res;
    }
};
```

