			while(start <= end){
				int mid = start + (end - start)/2;
				if(target*2 == arr[mid]) return true;
				else if(target*2 < arr[mid]) end = mid - 1;
				else start = mid + 1;
			}
		}
		return false;
	}
```
For the negative number test case such as: [-10,12,-20,-8,15], we get a sorted array [-20,-10,-8,12,15].
In this case -10 & -20 are a pair. Here if we use binary search in the forward direction then it will always return in false. That's why I added the if-else condition before the while-loop which will make the start and end position for checking. We can also abs() funciton while comparing in the while-loop, but I used this method instead. Thanks!

Update: I have uploaded another solution <a href="https://leetcode.com/problems/check-if-n-and-its-double-exist/discuss/1510247/C++-0ms-Beats-100-No-Fancy-or-Easy-Code">here</a>. It beats 100% and is 0ms runtime.

